, Durham, England":"Gainford, Durham, England","Streatlam, Durham, England":"Streatlam and Stainton, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Streatham Castle, Durham, England":"Durham, England","of Streatlam, Durham, Eng.":"Streatlam and Stainton, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Gainford Manor, Durham, England":"Gainford, Durham, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bowes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Bowes (formerly in North Yorkshire, now in County Durham), or from some other place so called, the placename being derived from the plural of Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow’, here referring to bends in a river. Alternatively, a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) arches or bridge’. See   Bow   1.","English: variant of   Bow  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Buadhaigh</b> (see   Bogue  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Bow","meanings":["Scottish and English: habitational name from any of various minor places called with Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow, arch, vault’, i.e. an arched bridge. There are places so called in Midlothian, Middlesex, and Devon.","Irish and English: variant of   Bowes  .","Chinese: possibly from Cantonese form of the Chinese names 寶 (meaning ‘treasure’) or 保 (meaning ‘protect’), which were monosyllabic personal names or part of disyllabic personal names of some early Chinese immigrants in the US."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":40,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":53,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":62,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Adam Bowes was born in 1275, in Gainford, Durham, England, United Kingdom as the son of Osbert De Bowes. He married Alice Trayne about 1322. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 28 March 1346, in Gainford, Durham, England, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1275–28 Mar 1346":"1275–28. märts 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1310–1350":"1310–1350","–Male":"Surnud","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","28 Mar 1346":"28. märts 1346","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1150":"1150","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1346":"1346","Abt 1322":"umbes 1322","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","liv. abt. 1310":"umbes 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Streatlam Castle, Gainford, Durham, England":"Gainford, Durham, England","Streatlam, Durham, England":"Streatlam and Stainton, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Streatham Castle, Durham, England":"Durham, England","of Streatlam, Durham, Eng.":"Streatlam and Stainton, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom